Here's a concise implementation of the `timezone_bumper` function in Julia:

```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime, bump::Int=3)
    return dt + Dates.Hour(bump)
end

function timezone_bumper(dt::Date, bump::Int=3)
    throw(ArgumentError("timezone_bumper only accepts DateTime types, not Date types."))
end
```

This function takes a `DateTime` object and an optional `bump` argument (which defaults to 3 hours) and returns a new `DateTime` object with the specified time offset. If a `Date` type is passed, the function will throw an `ArgumentError`.
